    summary: `Matthew's resurrection narrative begins with an earthquake — the second in the passion story — as an angel of the Lord descends from heaven, rolls back the stone, and sits on it. His appearance is "like lightning" and his clothes "white as snow." The guards shake with fear and become "like dead men." The irony is potent: the soldiers posted to guard a dead man are themselves rendered death-like, while the dead man is alive.

The angel addresses Mary Magdalene and "the other Mary": "Do not be afraid, for I know that you are looking for Jesus, who was crucified. He is not here; he has risen, just as he said." The women are instructed to go tell the disciples, and as they run — "afraid yet filled with joy" — Jesus himself meets them. They clasp his feet and worship him. His first word to them, as in so many post-resurrection appearances, is "Do not be afraid."

Matthew includes a detail unique to his Gospel: the chief priests bribe the soldiers to say the disciples stole the body while they slept. "And this story has been widely circulated among the Jews to this very day," Matthew notes — acknowledging and countering the earliest alternative explanation for the empty tomb.

The Gospel concludes on a mountain in Galilee, where the risen Jesus meets his disciples. Some worship; some doubt — Matthew refuses to smooth out the ambiguity. Jesus delivers the Great Commission: "All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. Therefore go and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit, and teaching them to obey everything I have commanded you. And surely I am with you always, to the very end of the age." The Gospel that began with "God with us" (Emmanuel, 1:23) ends with "I am with you always." The promise of presence frames the entire narrative.`,
    significance: `The resurrection is the event without which nothing else in the Gospel matters. As Paul puts it in 1 Corinthians, if Christ has not been raised, faith is futile. Matthew narrates the resurrection not as a resuscitation — a return to the same kind of life Jesus had before — but as a transformation. The risen Jesus has "all authority in heaven and on earth." He is not merely alive again; he is enthroned. The crucified teacher from Nazareth now exercises universal sovereignty.

The Great Commission is the final statement of Matthew's Gospel, and it redefines the scope of Jesus' mission. What began as a ministry focused on "the lost sheep of Israel" (10:6, 15:24) now extends to "all nations" (panta ta ethne). The universal scope of the mission matches the universal authority of the risen Jesus. And the content of the mission is not merely conversion — it is discipleship: "teaching them to obey everything I have commanded you." The Sermon on the Mount, the parables, the ethical teaching — all of it is part of what the nations are to learn and practice.`,
    relationalNote: `The women at the tomb — faithful when the male disciples had fled — are the first witnesses to the resurrection. In a culture where women's testimony was not considered legally valid, this detail is either historically accurate or a remarkably counterproductive invention. The church's founding proclamation rests on the testimony of women who were marginalized by their own society's standards of credibility.

The final scene includes the extraordinary detail that "some doubted" — even in the presence of the risen Jesus. Matthew does not identify who doubted or resolve the doubt. He simply includes it. The Great Commission is given to a community that is worshiping and doubting simultaneously. The mission of the church does not require the elimination of doubt — it requires obedience in the midst of doubt. The commission is given not to the certain but to the willing.`,
    conceptualNote: `The promise "I am with you always" (ego meith' hymon eimi) echoes the divine name — "I am" — and the promise made to Moses, Joshua, and the prophets. It is not a promise of subjective feeling ("you will feel my presence") but an ontological claim: the risen Christ is actually present with his people regardless of their awareness of it. The presence is not contingent on the disciples' faith, emotions, or spiritual state. It is a fact about reality.

Matthew's Gospel has a chiastic structure: it begins with Emmanuel ("God with us") and ends with "I am with you always." The entire narrative is framed by divine presence. The God who became present in the incarnation remains present through the resurrection. The mode changes — from physical body to spiritual presence — but the fact does not. The church exists in the space created by this promise: between the resurrection and the "end of the age," sustained by the presence of the one who has all authority.`,
    climateNote: `The mountain in Galilee where Jesus delivers the Great Commission is unidentified, but the return to Galilee is significant. The disciples are sent back to where they started — back to the fishing boats, the hillsides, the ordinary landscape of their pre-Jerusalem lives. The resurrection does not relocate them to a sacred space; it transforms the meaning of the space they already inhabit. The ordinary world is now the site of universal mission.

The earthquake that accompanies the resurrection connects it to the earthquake at the crucifixion, forming a seismic frame around the central events. In a region familiar with earthquakes, the geological disruption serves as a sign that the created order itself is responding to what has happened. The world has been shaken and reconstituted.`,
    modernParallel: `The Great Commission is the most consequential set of instructions in the history of the world. It has launched global missionary movements, built hospitals and schools on every continent, translated the Bible into over 3,000 languages, and shaped the political, cultural, and demographic map of the modern world. It has also been used to justify colonialism, cultural imperialism, and the destruction of indigenous traditions. The commission itself is neither colonialist nor liberating — it is a charge to make disciples, and the character of the discipleship determines whether the mission produces freedom or oppression.

The phrase "teaching them to obey everything I have commanded you" is the most underemphasized part of the Great Commission. Churches have been extraordinarily effective at the "go" and the "baptize" — less so at the "teach to obey." The gap between conversion and formation, between belief and practice, between getting people in the door and helping them become the kind of people the Sermon on the Mount describes — this gap is the central challenge of contemporary Christianity.

"Some doubted" is the most encouraging sentence in the resurrection narrative, because it means the church was never a community of the certain. From the very beginning, faith and doubt coexisted in the same group, in the same moment, in the presence of the risen Lord. The commission is not contingent on the elimination of doubt. It is given to people who worship and waver simultaneously. If doubt disqualified, the church would never have started. The presence of the risen Christ is not dependent on the certainty of his followers — it depends on the reality of the resurrection, which is independent of anyone's opinion about it.`,
